# 💍 One Last Swipe — Setup Guide

## File structure

```
your-folder/
├── index.html        ← the app
├── profiles.json     ← your profiles (edit this!)
├── lucas.jpg         ← photos (filenames must match "photo" in JSON)
├── antoine.jpg
└── ...
```

---

## Editing profiles.json

Each profile is an object with these fields:

| Field | Description | Example |
|---|---|---|
| `name` | First name | `"Lucas"` |
| `age` | Age shown on card | `28` |
| `job` | Job title (emoji welcome) | `"Chef 👨‍🍳"` |
| `distance` | Fake distance shown | `"2 km away"` |
| `bio` | Short tagline | `"Will cook for you."` |
| `flirt` | Completes "To flirt with me, you should:" | `"ask me about the sauce"` |
| `photo` | Exact filename of the photo | `"lucas.jpg"` |
| `forcedMatch` | `true` = always a match on right-swipe. `false` = ~35% random chance | `true` or `false` |

> 💡 **Match strategy**: set `forcedMatch: true` for the ones you want to guarantee fire up the confetti, and `false` for random ones that keep everyone on their toes.

---

## How to use it

### Option A — Drag & drop (easiest)
1. Open `index.html` in a browser
2. Select **all files** (index.html, profiles.json, photos) and drag them onto the drop zone
3. Done — start swiping!

### Option B — GitHub Pages
1. Push the whole folder to a GitHub repo
2. Go to **Settings → Pages → Deploy from branch** → select `main` / `root`
3. Share the URL with the group

### Option C — Local server (for developers)
```bash
npx serve .
# or
python -m http.server 8080
```

---

## Tips

- Photos can be JPG, PNG, WebP — whatever you have
- Filename matching is **case-sensitive** on some systems (`Lucas.jpg` ≠ `lucas.jpg`)
- Shuffle happens automatically on load so order in the JSON doesn't matter
- The ❤️ counter in the top right tracks matches in real time

Have an amazing bachelorette party! 🥂
